# Deploy slac-ood-opencode

Advances the `prod` branch to match `main` and pushes it to GitHub. The gitclone
sidecar in the OOD Kubernetes overlay pulls from this branch, so a pod restart is
the final step to pick up the new code.

## When to Use

- After merging work to `main` that should go live in the OOD app
- After adding/changing `form.yml.erb`, `template/`, `manifest.yml`, or any app file
- Whenever the user says "deploy", "release", or "ship this"

---

## Step 1 — Verify `main` is clean and ahead of `prod`

```bash
git status                                     # must be clean
git log --oneline prod..main                   # commits to be promoted — review these
git merge-base --is-ancestor prod main \
  && echo "prod is ancestor of main (fast-forward safe)" \
  || echo "WARNING: prod is not ancestor of main — investigate before proceeding"
```

If there are no commits in `prod..main`, there is nothing to deploy — stop and
tell the user.

## Step 2 — Fast-forward local `prod` to `main`

```bash
git update-ref refs/heads/prod refs/heads/main
git log --oneline -3 prod                      # confirm
```

## Step 3 — Push `prod` to remote

Use the explicit refspec to avoid tag/branch ambiguity (a `prod` tag may exist
on the remote):

```bash
# Delete remote prod tag if it exists (silently ignore if absent)
git push origin :refs/tags/prod 2>/dev/null || true

# Push branch explicitly
git push origin refs/heads/prod:refs/heads/prod --force-with-lease
```

If `--force-with-lease` fails, the remote has commits that aren't local. Fetch
and investigate before retrying:

```bash
git fetch origin prod
git log --oneline prod..origin/prod            # what's on remote that isn't local?
```

## Step 4 — Update the live sidecar (no restart needed)

The emptyDir is populated once at pod start by the gitclone init container. After
pushing `prod`, the running sidecar can pick up the new code immediately with a
`git pull` — no pod restart required:

```bash
export KUBECONFIG=/sdf/home/y/ytl/.kube/contexts/ondemand-dev/dev
POD=$(kubectl -n dev get pods -l app=ondemand -o name | head -1)
kubectl -n dev exec ${POD} -c slac-ood-opencode -- git -C /app pull origin prod
```

To force a full restart instead (e.g. if the sidecar is stuck):

```bash
# Dev overlay
kubectl -n dev rollout restart deployment/ondemand
kubectl -n dev rollout status  deployment/ondemand

# Prod overlay (only when explicitly requested by user)
kubectl -n prod rollout restart deployment/ondemand
kubectl -n prod rollout status  deployment/ondemand
```

**Never restart the prod overlay unless the user explicitly asks.**

## Step 5 — Verify

```bash
export KUBECONFIG=/sdf/home/y/ytl/.kube/contexts/ondemand-dev/dev
POD=$(kubectl -n dev get pods -l app=ondemand -o name | head -1)

# Check the slac-ood-opencode sidecar is on the right commit
kubectl -n dev exec ${POD} -c slac-ood-opencode -- git -C /app log --oneline -3

# Check app files are visible to the main container
kubectl -n dev exec ${POD} -c ondemand -- ls /var/www/ood/apps/sys/bc_opencode/
```

The HEAD commit shown in the sidecar should match `git log --oneline -1 prod`.

## Step 6 — Update TODO.md

After a successful deployment, update the relevant task's status to `🚀 Deployed`
in both the task file and `TODO.md`.

